#
# mstrap CLI surface (decoded from cli.cr):
#   Global flags (all persistent unless noted):
#     -c PATH / --config PATH    config file path (or HTTPS URL)
#                                (default: ~/.mstrap/mstrap.hcl)
#     -v / --verbose             verbose messaging
#     -V / --version             print version
#     -f / --force               force overwrite of existing config
#     --email EMAIL              email (non-persistent)
#     --github USERNAME          GitHub username (non-persistent)
#     --name NAME                Your name (non-persistent)
#     --skip-project-update      skip auto-update of projects
#
#   Subcommands (dynamic via Step.all + static project):
#     init                       initialize the machine
#     dependencies               install OS-level dependencies
#     shell                      configure shell environment
#     services                   set up local services
#     projects                   provision all configured projects
#     runtimes                   install language runtimes
#     project CNAME              provision a single project
#       --cname CNAME            project canonical name
#       --hostname HOST          project hostname
#                                (default: CNAME.localhost)
#       --name NAME              friendly project name
#       --port N                 port number
#       --path PATH              project path
#       --repo URL               git repository URL or GitHub path
#
# mstrap is a machine bootstrapping tool with a
# focus on SENSIBLE DEFAULTS, CONVENTIONS, and
# AVOIDANCE OF VENDORING.  Sets up new
# development machines via composable Step
# plugins (homebrew, asdf, nix, etc.).  Authored
# by Max Fierke (maxfierke).  24 GH stars (real
# production tool used at multiple companies).
# Sister tools: thoughtbot/laptop (BASH-based
# alternative), chef-bk-prep (Chef-based),
# strap (older Bash predecessor), boxen.
#
# Critical extraction note: mstrap uses **Crystal
# `commander.cr` library** at cli.cr:32 —
# corpus's **first documented commander.cr
# library** + **third documented Crystal CLI
# library** (joining R269 Crystal stdlib
# OptionParser + R299 Crystal Admiral).
# commander.cr is mrrooijen/commander, the Ruby
# Thor-inspired CLI builder for Crystal — 130 GH
# stars, MIT license, distributed via Crystal's
# `shards` package manager.  Distinct from R269
# Crystal stdlib OptionParser (`parser.on(...)`
# method-chain, no subcommands), R299 Crystal
# Admiral (CLASS-INHERITANCE-WITH-DSL via
# `class < Admiral::Command` + `define_flag`
# macros).  commander.cr's distinguishing
# features: BLOCK-BUILDER PATTERN (`Commander::
# Command.new do |cmd| ... end`), block-builder
# per flag with FIELD ASSIGNMENTS (`flag.short`,
# `flag.long`, `flag.persistent`), DYNAMIC
# subcommand registration via `.each do ... end`
# loops, HANDLER BLOCKS via `cmd.run do
# |options, arguments| ... end`.  Extends cross-
# language CLI taxonomy to SEVENTY-ONE library
# variants: Rust (7), Go (4), Python (3),
# **Crystal 1 OptionParser (R269)**, Haskell
# (R270), OCaml 1 Cmdliner (R271), C (R272),
# Java 1 picocli (R276), Kotlin (R277),
# Scala (R278), Dart (R279), Ruby (R280),
# Perl (R281), PHP (R282), Swift (R283),
# F# (R284), Lua (R285), C# (R286), Nim 1
# parseopt (R287), Zig (R288), D (R289),
# Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291),
# Erlang 1 getopt (R292), Tcl (R293), Pharo
# Smalltalk (R294), Common Lisp 2 clingon (R295),
# Julia (R296), SWI-Prolog optparse (R297), Pony
# stdlib cli (R298), **Crystal 2 Admiral (R299)**,
# V stdlib `flag` (R300), Nim 2 cligen (R301),
